questions.question:
Consider the following ES6 class structure:

```javascript
class Animal {
  constructor(name) {
    this.name = name;
  }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
  constructor(name, breed) {
    // Point A
    this.breed = breed;
    // Point B
    super(name);
    // Point C
  }
}
```

At which point(s) would calling `super(name)` result in an error or unexpected behavior, and why?

questions.example:
In ES6 derived class constructors, `super()` *must* be called before any `this` reference is made. This is because `super()` is responsible for initializing `this` for the derived class by invoking the parent class's constructor. Until `super()` is called, `this` is not yet defined in the child's constructor, leading to a `ReferenceError` if accessed.

Correct usage:
```javascript
class Dog extends Animal {
  constructor(name, breed) {
    super(name); // Call super first
    this.breed = breed; // Then access this
  }
}
```

